{"indexed":{"date-parts":[[2024,7,27]],"date-time":"2024-07-27T11:19:11Z","timestamp":1722079151729},"reference-count":71,"publisher":"Pensoft Publishers","license":[{"start":{"date-parts":[[2020,12,31]],"date-time":"2020-12-31T00:00:00Z","timestamp":1609372800000},"content-version":"vor","delay-in-days":0,"URL":"http:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by\/4.0\/"}],"funder":[{"DOI":"10.13039\/100000014","name":"Smithsonian Institution","doi-asserted-by":"publisher","id":[{"id":"10.13039\/100000014","id-type":"DOI","asserted-by":"publisher"}]}],"content-domain":{"domain":[],"crossmark-restriction":false},"abstract":"<jats:p>Robust data to refute or support claims of global insect decline are currently lacking, particularly for the soil fauna in the tropics. DNA metabarcoding represents a powerful approach for rigorous spatial and temporal monitoring of the taxonomically challenging soil fauna. Here, we provide a detailed field protocol, which was successfully applied in Barro Colorado Island (BCI) in Panama, to collect soil samples and arthropods in a tropical rainforest, to be later processed with metabarcoding. We also estimate the proportion of soil\/litter ant, springtail and termite species from the local fauna that can be detected by metabarcoding samples obtained either from Berlese-Tullgren (soil samples), Malaise or light traps. Each collecting method detected a rather distinct fauna. Soil and Malaise trap samples detected 213 species (73%) of all target species. Malaise trap samples detected many ant species, whereas soil samples were more efficient at detecting springtail and termite species. With respect to long-term monitoring of soil-dwelling and common species (more amenable to statistical trends), the best combination of two methods were soil and light trap samples, detecting 94% of the total of common species. A protocol including 100 soil, 40 Malaise and 80 light trap samples annually processed by metabarcoding would allow the long-term monitoring of at least 11%, 18% and 16% of species of soil\/litter ants, springtails and termites, respectively, present on BCI, and a high proportion of the total abundance (up to 80% of all individuals) represented by these taxa.<\/jats:p>","DOI":"10.3897\/mbmg.4.58572","type":"journal-article","created":{"date-parts":[[2020,12,31]],"date-time":"2020-12-31T16:01:26Z","timestamp":1609430486000},"source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":8,"title":"Methodological considerations for monitoring soil\/litter arthropods in tropical rainforests using DNA metabarcoding, with a special emphasis on ants, springtails and termites","prefix":"10.3897","volume":"4","author":[{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-1942-5717","authenticated-orcid":true,"given":"Yves","family":"Basset","sequence":"first","affiliation":[]},{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-3408-1457","authenticated-orcid":true,"given":"David A.","family":"Donoso","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Mehrdad","family":"Hajibabaei","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Michael T. G.","family":"Wright","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Kate H. J.","family":"Perez","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-7645-985X","authenticated-orcid":true,"given":"Greg P. A.","family":"Lamarre","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0001-9317-420X","authenticated-orcid":true,"given":"Luis F.","family":"De Le\u00f3n","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0001-9097-6813","authenticated-orcid":true,"given":"Jos\u00e9 G.","family":"Palacios-Vargas","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Gabriela","family":"Casta\u00f1o-Meneses","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Marleny","family":"Rivera","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Filonila","family":"Perez","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[]},{"given":"Ricardo","family":"Bobadilla",